<https://colonial-heritage.triply.cc/nmvw/id/object/RV-3513-1496> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#name> "HOKUSAI, ZELFPORTRET OP 83-JARIGE LEEFTIJD AAN HET EIND VAN EEN BRIEF AAN ZIJN UITGEVER" .
<https://colonial-heritage.triply.cc/nmvw/id/object/RV-3513-1496> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#publisher> "Nationaal Museum van Wereldculturen" .
<https://colonial-heritage.triply.cc/nmvw/id/object/RV-3513-1496> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Behalve de groep tekeningen van fabelleeuwen die Hokusai gedurende meer dan een jaar dagelijks als afweer tegen het kwaad tekende, zijn weinig tekeningen zo algemeen geaccepteerd als dit zelfportret van de kunstenaar op drieentachtigjarige leeftijd. Opvallend is hierbij dat de groep fabelleeuwen, bekend onder de naam Nisshin joma, ongeveer in dezelfde periode is ontstaan als dit zelfportret, namelijk 1842. Katsushika Hokusai (1760-1849) was een van de meest veelzijdige en productieve ukiyoe kunstenaars, in het westen vooral befaamd als ontwerper van de serie landschapsprenten 'De zesendertig gezichten op de berg Fuji'. In dit zelfportret zien we de kunstenaar als oude man, grijnzend, met de rechterhand naar de plaats wijzend waar oorspronkelijk de naam van de geadresseerde heeft gestaan. De tekst rechts is namelijk een brief die, gezien de inhoud, aan een van Hokusai's uitgevers gericht lijkt te zijn. Het is echter niet mogelijk de identiteit van deze uitgever met enige zekerheid vast te stellen. De tekst van de brief luidt: 'Welnu, de schetsen in dit deel zijn uit de tijd dat ik zo'n een- of tweeenveertigjaar oud was. Bovendien is er een aantal die elkaar dupliceren. Enkele zouden nu, na al die jaren, beter uitgewerkt kunnen worden. De rest kan als onrijp werk uit vroeger tijd afgedaan worden en u moogt er om lachen. Hoogachtend, de drieentachtigjarige Hachiemon, [zegel:] Manji'.\r\nHet is interessant aan de hand van dit zelfportret na te kunnen gaan dat Hokusai - evenals dit bijvoorbeeld veelvuldig in het werk van Rembrandt het geval is - in enkele andere tekeningen en schilderingen uit dezelfde periode, zichzelf voor ogen had. Onder meer zijn vrijwel identieke gelaatstrekken herkenbaar in een portret van een oude man (RMV 2736-2) en in een schildering van de dondergod Raijin, in de collectie van de Freer Gallery of Art, Smithsonian Institution (00.47), geschilderd op achtentachtigjarige leeftijd. (MF)\r\n\r\nEngelse tekst:\r\nBesides the group of drawings of legendary animals which Hokusai made daily for more than a year to ward off evil, few of his drawings are as widely accepted as his work as this self-portrait of the artist at the age of eighty-three. It is noteworthy in this connection that the series of legendary animals, known under the name of Nisshin joma, dates from roughly the same period as this portrait, i.e., 1842. Katsushika Hokusai (1760-1849) was one of the most versatile and productive ukiyoe artists and is known best as the designer of the series of landscape prints called 'Thirty-six views of Mount Fuji'. In this portrait we see the artist as an old man, a wry smile on his face, with his right hand pointing to the place where the name of the addressee was originally placed, the text at the right being a letter whose contents suggest that it was intended for one of Hokusai's publishers. It has not been possible to establish the name of this publisher with certainty. The text of the letter reads: 'Well then, the sketches in this volume were done when I was about forty-one or forty-two. Furthermore, there are a number duplicating each other. Some of them might, after all these years, better be worked out. The remainder can be regarded as immature work from the past, which you may smile about. Sincerefy yours, the eighty-three-year old Hachiemon, [seal:] Manji.' It is interesting to compare this self-portrait with other drawings and paintings from the same period to see whether Hokusai used - as Rembrandt, for example, often did - himself as model. Almost identical facial features can be recognized in, among others, a portrait of an old man (RMV 2736-2) and a painting of the thunder god Raijin in the collection of the Freer Gallery of Art (Smithsonian Institution, no. 00.47) painted by Hokusai at the age of eighty-three.\r\n\r\nDescription as written for the ASEMUS virtual masterpieces project\r\n\r\nKatsushika Hokusai: Self-portrait at the End of a Letter\r\nBorn in 1760 in a suburbian area of Edo, present-day Tokyo, Hokusai first trained with a mirror polisher, then with a cutter of woodblocks for printing popular novels, to finally enrol in the studio of Katsukawa Shunsho, apparently aiming for a career as a designer of prints of kabuki actors in role. Finally, around 1791, he saw something of recognition when the great publisher Tsutaya Jusaburo commissioned him to design some actor prints. However, soon after, he gave up, turned to the world of amateur poets where he found great appreciation for his illustrations to their poetry anthologies, then shifting to commercial publishing to end his career as the foremost illustrator of popular novels. In his fifties, he realized that maybe the time had come to leave the world his legacy, which he laid down in a series of albums serving as a guide for those who wanted to follow and learn the 'Hokusai-style of drawing'. But he did not die yet, and, remarkably, all of his works which would give him world fame as one of the greatest artists of all eras - e.g. the Thirty-Six Views of Mount Fuji - were created when he was in his seventies. This probably inspired him to write, aged seventy-five, a brief autobiography in which he asked for some more years, since 'Consequently, by the age of eighty-six I will have made more and more progress, and at ninety I will have got closer to the essence of art. At the age of one hundred I will have reached a magnificent level and at one hundred and ten each dot and each line will be alive.' In the same text, he mentions in passing that 'none of my works done before my seventieth is really worth counting.' \r\nIn this letter which he wrote to some of his publishers to accompany some of his earlier work, he demonstrates the same wisdom:\r\n'Well then, the designs in this album were done when I was about forty-one or forty-two. Moreover, a few are duplicating each other. Some of them might, after all these years, better be worked out. The remainder can be seen as immature work from the past which you may smile about. Sincerely yours, the eighty-three year old Hachiemon [sealed:] Manji' - Manji, translating as Ten Thousand Years, being the art-name Hokusai then used. This insight, or wisdom, paired with the self-portrait of a smiling old man, with eyes full of wit, but at the same time drawn in such a sure hand, qualifies this in all respects impromptu work as a great masterpiece.\r\n\r\nAdditional:\r\nThis letter/drawing was acquired by the Dutch collector Ferdinand Lieftinck (1879-1959), a tobacco merchant at Groningen, from the art dealer Felix Tikotin. Lieftinck had been a collector of Japanese art from the 1930s, selling his first collection in 1938 and subsequently focussing on only the very best. In 1956 he offered his collection for sale to the Netherlands and his collection of some 237 Japanese prints would then form the nucleus of the Japanese collection of the Amsterdam Rijksmuseum, still continued until today. At the time, his collection of some more than 4,000 sketches and drawings were considered as of an ethnographic nature and landed in the Leiden National Museum of Ethnology, this letter/drawing among this group." .
